34:50.337 --> 34:55.082
They're intoxicated with the scent of their own perfumes.

34:55.501 --> 35:02.236
And the other book becomes a bestseller, and the next thing you know, they think of themselves as writers.

35:02.256 --> 35:03.819
And I don't think of themselves as writers.

35:03.839 --> 35:05.763
I think of them as lucky amateurs.

35:05.783 --> 35:06.565
Sure.

35:06.585 --> 35:13.600
Well, you look at it, and I'm not asking you to comment and say it to Tom Clancy, for instance, but I don't think you've read any of his books.

35:13.620 --> 35:14.843
Never.

35:15.616 --> 35:22.746
I think it's a case where he probably represents 10 or 15 or 20 percent of the gross of Putnam's, and they're afraid to edit him.

35:22.886 --> 35:25.650
But, I mean, you can't touch his copy, is what I hear.

35:25.690 --> 35:26.231
I don't know.

35:26.251 --> 35:32.860
1,300-page books, you know, that could probably be told nearly 400 pages, you know.

35:35.103 --> 35:36.766
But his ego takes over.

35:36.866 --> 35:37.607
I read this book.

35:38.684 --> 35:41.788
Now we're back home.

35:42.709 --> 35:44.110
Now we're back home.

35:44.130 --> 35:46.313
Can we just finish with the amateur thing?

35:46.433 --> 35:46.994
Sure.

35:47.394 --> 35:55.284
So it just, it irks me.

35:55.884 --> 36:04.995
I feel people should, you know, I wouldn't let a guy come in off the street and take out my appendix.

36:06.308 --> 36:10.114
without having gone to medical school and knowing there was something about surgery.

36:10.154 --> 36:15.482
And it seems to me some guy shouldn't come out of the street and write a novel without any background.

36:16.323 --> 36:25.076
Well, everybody certainly has the right to try, whether or not it should be acclaimed as the greatest thing since the day of the jackpot.

36:25.156 --> 36:26.959
You know, I think we're sending a message.

36:27.740 --> 36:34.290
I think we're sending the jackpot message to America that anybody can sit down with no training or anything and write a book,

36:35.317 --> 36:36.679
And it can be illiterate.

36:36.699 --> 36:40.025
It can be the worst prose that you've ever read in your life.

36:40.927 --> 36:48.139
And you can hit the big million-dollar, multi-million-dollar jackpot, and it'll be a movie, and number one on the bestseller list, and all that.

36:48.640 --> 36:50.283
And that's a wrong message, essentially.

36:50.303 --> 36:52.066
It's against the work ethic, to me.

36:52.086 --> 36:53.228
To me, it drives me nuts.

36:53.328 --> 36:57.375
One of the reasons my book was canceled at Random House is because they had so little money.

36:57.811 --> 37:02.725
tied up with me, and they had tons, millions upon millions, tied up with the plot.

37:02.745 --> 37:05.594
You know, they have, I mean, for other writers.

37:05.714 --> 37:09.525
Yeah, I mean, for writers who have spent five or six years on public,

37:09.961 --> 37:11.022
who deserve a shot.

37:11.743 --> 37:15.186
All of a sudden, they're losing their ass on guns.

37:15.366 --> 37:17.528
They've got to cut it someplace else.

37:17.709 --> 37:23.955
Not only is it not right for the message it sends out, it's not right for the other serious writers who are working.

37:24.335 --> 37:32.583
Well, you see, the publisher will say, yeah, but when we make money on these blockbusters, then this allows us to print poetry and serious fiction.

37:32.603 --> 37:34.585
Number one, they don't print poetry anymore.

37:34.685 --> 37:37.808
Number two, the November 1st novel that you see was

37:37.940 --> 37:39.382
Yeah, but we have time.

37:39.402 --> 37:39.582
Okay.

37:39.622 --> 37:40.664
Well, we've got ten minutes.

37:40.684 --> 37:40.964
Okay.

37:41.405 --> 37:43.368
Let's tell you a little, you know, a quote.

37:43.388 --> 37:44.690
I've got the quotes elsewhere.

37:44.750 --> 37:51.941
I mean, like Bob Parker Spencer does age at about three-quarter speed, you know, in real life.

37:52.061 --> 37:54.985
But your 87th Precinct stuff is really fixed.

37:55.626 --> 37:56.647
They're all 30-something.

37:56.888 --> 37:57.188
Yeah.

37:57.268 --> 37:58.370
They're still all 30-something.

37:58.771 --> 38:01.234
Haven't you ever thought about bringing them along with you a little bit?

38:01.394 --> 38:03.137
No, because then they'd be dung.

38:03.370 --> 38:04.571
Daughtering old fools.

38:05.533 --> 38:07.755
Investigating crimes.

38:07.775 --> 38:10.719
They'll be coming in on walkers.

38:11.100 --> 38:12.581
Lieutenant Burns will be in a wheelchair.

38:12.621 --> 38:14.564
What's going on, Steve?

38:15.064 --> 38:17.147
But the readers don't complain about this.

38:17.267 --> 38:18.128
They accept it.

38:18.228 --> 38:19.630
Some of them get confused by it.

38:19.790 --> 38:20.992
I get a letter every now and then.

38:21.152 --> 38:26.539
How come the twins were born and they're still only 10 years old?

38:26.719 --> 38:27.940
I sent them a chapter from it.

38:27.960 --> 38:30.363
A guy wrote a book about the 85th Precinct.

38:30.383 --> 38:33.327
And I sent them his chapter from...

38:34.235 --> 38:38.941
The elastic calendar and the perpetual clock or something like that.

38:38.961 --> 38:40.283
And I just send them that chapter.

38:40.803 --> 38:42.626
So here, read this and we'll explain the whole work.

38:42.646 --> 38:43.567
That's great.

38:43.587 --> 38:44.828
That's great.

38:44.848 --> 38:47.612
Are you happy to be back with Levin Hunter again?

38:47.652 --> 38:47.912
Yeah.

38:48.834 --> 38:50.816
So are we going to wait another ten years for the next one?

38:50.836 --> 38:50.976
No, no.

38:50.996 --> 38:53.159
I've been working on another one anyway.

38:54.481 --> 38:56.123
That's a very ambitious book.

38:56.363 --> 38:58.446
And I hope I get it right.

38:58.486 --> 39:00.208
I haven't got it right yet, but I will.

39:00.323 --> 39:06.375
It starts in ancient Sumeria, and it comes up to today, through the ages.

39:06.435 --> 39:14.231
So it's a big, fat book, and it'll probably be... I think it's the best thing I've ever done, if I ever get it right.

39:14.251 --> 39:15.333
I haven't got it right yet.

39:15.353 --> 39:15.934
I'll get it right.

39:16.295 --> 39:22.247
Does it bother you that writers of mystery... Of course, it's changing, but are...

39:23.645 --> 39:29.492
in some cases dismissed by the literati as genre writers.

39:30.033 --> 39:30.774
It used to bother me.

39:30.794 --> 39:32.255
It doesn't any longer.

39:32.596 --> 39:37.702
There are about ten old men in Sweden deciding on who gets the Nobel Prize.

39:37.722 --> 39:43.068
And even then it's very political.

39:43.088 --> 39:44.390
Graham Greene never got it.

39:44.430 --> 39:45.752
But Edna Furbin did.

39:45.772 --> 39:47.233
But Edna Furbin did, yeah.

39:47.253 --> 39:49.416
Sort of Pearl S. Buck.

39:50.425 --> 39:51.728
Remember Pearl Buck?

39:51.748 --> 39:52.089
Sure.

39:52.149 --> 39:52.951
One book.

39:53.111 --> 39:54.374
Yeah, The Good Earth.

39:54.414 --> 39:55.556
Well, Dragon Seed.

39:55.616 --> 39:58.302
Yeah, one book that certainly has stood the test of time.

39:58.322 --> 39:59.204
Yeah, Tony Morrison.

39:59.224 --> 40:02.411
You know, does she deserve to know about that?

40:02.432 --> 40:03.915
Eight, nine books.

40:03.935 --> 40:05.318
Politically correct.

40:05.338 --> 40:06.541
Of course.

40:06.561 --> 40:08.786
Would you kindly be honored on this?

40:08.926 --> 40:09.447
Indeed me.

